======================================================================
PART 2: COUNTING DIRECTED CYCLES CORRECTLY
======================================================================

On a set of k vertices, a directed cycle visits each vertex once
in cyclic order. The number of distinct directed k-cycles on k
labeled vertices is (k-1)! (fixing one vertex, permuting the rest).
But in a tournament, at most SOME of these are actually directed.

For 3 vertices: (3-1)! = 2 possible directed 3-cycles.
A tournament on 3 vertices has exactly 1 or 0 directed 3-cycles.
(It's 1 iff the tournament is NOT transitive.)

For 5 vertices: (5-1)! = 24 possible directed 5-cycles.
But as directed CYCLES: we identify cyclic rotations,
so (5-1)! / 5... no, (5-1)! already fixes one vertex.
Actually: there are (5-1)!/2 = 12 distinct unoriented cycles,
each giving 1 directed cycle. So up to 12 directed 5-cycles.

T0: H=9, #3-cycles=3, #directed-5-cycles=1
  All cycles are on overlapping vertices at n=5
  α₁=4, α₂=0 (complete conflict graph)
  I(2) = 1 + 2·4 = 9
  Match? True

T1: H=9, #3-cycles=3, #directed-5-cycles=1
  All cycles are on overlapping vertices at n=5
  α₁=4, α₂=0 (complete conflict graph)
  I(2) = 1 + 2·4 = 9
  Match? True

